}}'''''Grand Slam: World Class Tennis''''' is a 1986 video game published by [[Infinity Software]] for [[Macintosh]] and [[Amiga]].

==Development==
''Grand Slam: World Class Tennis'' was originally a simple tennis game developed by [[MacroMind]]. Former tennis professional Tom Maremaa bought the code and worked with two programmers to develop it into a full-featured tennis simulation.<ref name="MacUser" /><ref>{{cite web
|url=https://www.tommaremaa.com/notebooks-1/2019/1/24/tennis-down-under-above-and-beyond
|title=Tennis Down Under, Above and Beyond
|date=January 24, 2019
|last=Maremaa
|first= Tom
|publisher=www.tommaremaa.com
|via=[[Squarespace]]
|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230927163435/https://www.tommaremaa.com/notebooks-1/2019/1/24/tennis-down-under-above-and-beyond
|archive-date=September 27, 2023
|accessdate=September 28, 2023
|url-status=live
}}</ref> The game was initially released on Macintosh in 1986. An Amiga port was released later that year.

==Gameplay==
[[Image:Grand-slam-world-class-tennis 1.png|thumb|250px|Loading screen]]
''Grand Slam: World Class Tennis'' is a game in which the [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] tournament is played.<ref name="CGW31"/>

==Reception==
Frank C. Boosman reviewed the game for ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'', and stated that "I like to think of GS as a diamond in the rough: pretty, but even more so once it has been cut and polished."<ref name="CGW31">{{cite magazine |last=Boosman |first=Frank C. |title=Macintosh Windows |magazine=Computer Gaming World |date=September–October 1986 |volume=1 |issue=31 |pages=6–7}}</ref>

David M. Wilson and Johnny L. Wilson reviewed the game for ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'', and stated that "the action is where it is at and Grand Slam Tennis is an action game which is sophisticated enough to know that position is truly important in tennis."<ref name="CGW46">{{cite magazine |last1=Wilson |first1=David M. |last2=Wilson |first2=Johnny L. |title=The Boys of Spring: A Computer Sports Survey |magazine=Computer Gaming World |date=April 1988 |volume=1 |issue=46 |pages=14, 16}}</ref>

''[[MacUser]]'' awarded the game 4 out of 5 mice, saying the game succeeded "both as a simulation and a highly addictive game" despite occasionally choppy controls.<ref name="MacUser">{{cite journal
